arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.

Locus 40 is the soil below the collapse in the west of the trench (Locus 39), north of the colonnade wall. The soil is a dark gray (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/3) silt, with inclusions of pottery, bone, metal, shell, and glass. There is an especially large amount of pottery, and there were additionally a number of pieces of opus sectile. It seems that this locus was originally below a floor that would have covered the whole area in the west of the trench, of which a small section is still intact (Locus 79). The uniformity of the soil, its clear difference from the collapse above, and its relation to the intact floor all lead to this conclusion. Locus 40 is therefore phased to Stage 2, the main construction of the Roman Bath Complex.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.
10.00 m north south -by- 9.20 m east west.
